surname>Shah</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF026137%2F1"><gtr:id>D75A223C-7554-418B-98CB-23E27D03D79D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Ethnicity, Religion &amp;amp; Citizenship among the Children of Immigrants in the UK and USA</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F026137/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>In the aftermath of ?9/11? in New York and ?7/7? in London, questions of loyalty, belonging and citizenship have become urgent in the USA and UK. This social and political context calls for a renewed examination of the place of faith communities within multicultural societies, the nature of citizenship and national identity, and the ways in which people?s identities are shaped by local sentiments and a sense of a global diaspora. This three-year programme of work will address these themes through: a) a book on second-generation Laotian girls participating in an environmental justice organisation in California, USA. The in-depth case study will document their adaptation experiences, offer an opportunity to examine grassroots political organisations as sites of immigrant incorporation, and highlight the ways in which citizenship in the USA is a gendered, classed and racial formation; b) this book will form the context for a new qualitative research project that will investigate the role of religion and religious institutions in shaping identity, belonging and citizenship among young Jains in the UK and USA; and c) a series of&amp;nbsp; three interdisciplinary workshops, titled ?Faith in Suburbia?, which will focus on the emergence and significance of new religious institutional spaces in London.
