No known notable impacts</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6652832242.3368992ab6850e</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other academic audiences (collaborators, peers etc.)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2013</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Research funded through this grant has discovered:
a) the Jain tradition provides a resource for young Jains to deal with risks and uncertainties in modern societies, young Jains are reconstructing a Jain identity through dietary practices, for young Jains in the USA Jain principles inform commitments to formal politics and civic engagement.
b) my research challenges dominant notions of suburbia as secular and homogenous, and diasporic faith groups draw on distinctive elements of their suburban locations to create religious spaces.
c) my book on second-generation Laotians in the USA has found that citizenship as social practice is not just an adult experience, and ethnicity is a durable force in the political and social identities of second-generation Laotians in the USA.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Findings from research on young Jains in the UK and USA have informed the development of an application to the Heritage Lottery Fund for an oral history project on the British Jain community. This application will be submitted by an non-academic stakeholder and I am acting as a consultant on the application and potential project.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>DB84497B-14EA-4C2A-A394-5D715FA4D3D8</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>545d4459906247.69120769</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E4C03AAD-470A-49E2-B0F7-60DF652B18B3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Negotiating multiculturalism : religion and the organisation of jain identity in contemporary Britain and USA</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>NA</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/69723c01269e51ee0f950e932d0f9e22"><gtr:id>69723c01269e51ee0f950e932d0f9e22</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames> Bindi Shah (author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:outcomeId>r_2302662612cbdde844</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>78B15B7F-A83E-4E5D-BA8C-7CE26C4AEC56</gtr:id><gtr:title>The sacred in suburbia : new landscapes of diasporic religious belonging</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1fe5c75f93d53649bfcd5baa62347e9e"><gtr:id>1fe5c75f93d53649bfcd5baa62347e9e